<content>
    
    <para id="id10406899">An issue with ionization potential and electron affinity is that they are defined and measured as reactions in the gas phase. Although values have been determined for molecular fragments it is still difficult to correlate with reaction trends in solution. To overcome this issue the concept of electronegativity was developed. </para>
    
    <para id="id10406968">Electronegativity is defined as the <emphasis effect="italics">tendency of an atom in a molecule to attract electrons to itself</emphasis>. Although several electronegativity scales have been developed, that by Linus Pauling (<link target-id="id10407106"/>) is the most often used. <link target-id="id10407182"/> provides selected Pauling electronegativity values (unit less). </para>
